******
[2] North Carolina
Date: Thu 18 Jul 2013
Source: Star News Online [edited]
http://www.starnewsonline.com/article/20130718/ARTICLES/130719619?Title=3DMosquito-borne-disease-kills-Brunswick-horse


A Brunswick County horse has died after contracting eastern equine encephalitis (EEE).

The North Carolina Department of Agriculture confirmed the death, which was the 1st confirmed case of EEE in the state this year [2013]. In 2012, there were 20 veterinary cases in North Carolina and 2 human cases. Brunswick County had one case of each.

In a statement, Brunswick County Health Director David Stanley cautioned residents to protect themselves against EEE and other mosquito-borne illnesses. He urged residents to wear light-colored long pants and shirts and to avoid exposure at dusk and dawn, when mosquitoes are most active.

Jeff Brown, Brunswick County's vector control supervisor, said EEE is spread primarily by mosquitoes that live in floodplains or saltwater marshes.

EEE is a viral illness that attacks the central nervous system and can be fatal to animals and humans. There is a vaccine for horses, but not for humans. Stanley urged horse owners to ensure that their animals are properly vaccinated.

[Byline: Mike Voorheis]

